{"title_page": "Super Free", "text_new": "{{Infobox organization\n| name                = Super Free\n| native_name         = \u30b9\u30fc\u30d1\u30fc\u30d5\u30ea\u30fc\n| former_name         =\n| image               = \n| image_border        =\n| size                = <!-- default 200px -->\n| alt                 = <!-- alt text; see [[WP:ALT]] -->\n| caption             = \n| map                 =\n| map_size            = <!-- map size, optional, default 250px -->\n| map_alt             = <!-- map alt text -->\n| map_caption         =\n| map2                =\n| abbreviation        =\n| motto               =\n| predecessor         =\n| successor           =\n| formation           = 1982\n| founder             = <!-- or | founders = -->\n| dissolution         = 2003\n| merger              =\n| merged              =\n| type                = [[Yugen kaisha]]\n| status              = <!-- ad hoc, treaty, foundation, etc -->\n| purpose             = <!-- focus as e.g. humanitarian, peacekeeping, etc -->\n| professional_title  = <!-- for professional associations -->\n| headquarters        = \n| location            = \n| coords              = <!-- Coordinates of location using {{Coord}} -->\n| region_served       = [[Japan]]\n| services            =\n| membership          =\n| language            = \n| general             = <!-- Secretary General -->\n| leader_title        =\n| leader_name         =\n| leader_title2       =\n| leader_name2        =\n| leader_title3       =\n| leader_name3        =\n| leader_title4       =\n| leader_name4        =\n| board_of_directors  =\n| key_people          =\n| main_organ          = <!-- gral. assembly, board of directors, etc -->\n| parent_organization = \n| subsidiaries        =\n| affiliations        =\n| budget              =\n| num_staff           =\n| num_volunteers      =\n| slogan              =\n}}\n\n{{nihongo|'''Super Free'''|\u30b9\u30fc\u30d1\u30fc\u30d5\u30ea\u30fc|S\u016bp\u0101-fur\u012b}} or its shortened form {{nihongo|'''S\u016bfuri'''|\u30b9\u30fc\u30d5\u30ea}} was an inter-university rave event club, mainly comprising students of [[Waseda University]] in [[Tokyo]], [[Japan]]. The leader of the club along with various students from Waseda and other universities in Tokyo was arrested and convicted for rape and, subsequently, the club was dubbed by several English media outlets as a \"rape club\".<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.timesonline.co.uk/tol/life_and_style/article1165356.ece|title=Rape clubs: A stain on its elite students that Japan cannot face|first=Leo|last=Lewis|publisher=[[The Times]]|date=2003-10-03|accessdate=2010-09-02}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cbsnews.com/stories/2003/09/02/world/main571280.shtml|title=Rape Debate In Japan|first=Lauren|last=Johnston|publisher=[[CBS]]|date=2003-09-02|accessdate=2010-09-02}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.abc.net.au/news/stories/2004/11/02/1233322.htm|title=Elite club leader gets 14 years jail for gang rapes|publisher=[[ABC Online]]|date=2004-11-02|accessdate=2010-09-02}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.smh.com.au/articles/2003/07/04/1057179159324.html|title=Japan searches soul after divisive rape case|first=Shane|last=Green|publisher=[[The Sydney Morning Herald]]|date=2003-07-05|accessdate=2010-09-02}}</ref> Its leader was {{nihongo|Shin'ichir\u014d Wada|\u548c\u7530 \u771f\u4e00\u90ce|''Wada Shin'ichir\u014d''|born July 30, 1974, in [[Kawasaki, Kanagawa|Kawasaki]], [[Kanagawa Prefecture]]}}. Members of the group were convicted of raping three women, but the real number of victims is unknown.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/worldnews/asia/japan/1475762/Student-rape-mastermind-jailed.html |title=Student rape mastermind jailed |publisher=[[The Daily Telegraph|Telegraph]] |date=2004-11-03| accessdate=2008-07-02 | location=London | first=Colin | last=Joyce}}</ref> Since their arrests, and the club's dissolution, twelve other women have been identified as victims.<ref name=\"gang rape\">{{\ncite news\n | first = Deborah | last = Cameron\n | url=http://www.theage.com.au/articles/2004/11/03/1099362217587.html?from=storylhs\n | title=Gang rape club lured Tokyo girls\n | newspaper = [[The Age|Age]]\n | publisher= [[Fairfax Media|Fairfax]]\n | date=2004-11-04| accessdate=2008-01-17\n| location=Melbourne}}</ref> The club was also incorporated as {{nihongo| Super Free [[Y\u016bgen gaisha]] (Limited)|\u6709\u9650\u4f1a\u793e\u30b9\u30fc\u30d1\u30fc\u30d5\u30ea\u30fc}}.\n\nSuper Free was established as a university social club in 1982.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://search.japantimes.co.jp/cgi-bin/nn20040409a3.html|title=College gang-rape trio get up to 32 months|publisher=The Japan Times|date=2004-04-09|accessdate=2009-07-10}}</ref> Wada was a student at Waseda University before being arrested.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.theage.com.au/cgi-bin/common/popupPrintArticle.pl?path=/articles/2003/07/04/1057179156476.html |title=Revealed: the workings of a uni rape club |publisher=[[The Age]] |date=2003-07-05 |access-date=2008-01-17 |location=Melbourne |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071121093616/http://www.theage.com.au/cgi-bin/common/popupPrintArticle.pl?path=%2Farticles%2F2003%2F07%2F04%2F1057179156476.html |archive-date=2007-11-21 |url-status=dead |df= }}</ref> He entered Waseda University in 1994 and became the organizer of \"Super Free\" in 1995. It had 14 members as of 2003. Super Free was a highly successful inter-university rave event club, to the point that it was incorporated, having 5 branches nationwide, 30-odd employees and an office in Roppongi. According to the indictment, the club organized parties and social gatherings at a public night-club in [[Roppongi]]. The members of Super Free would scout for potential victims among the public, and befriend them offering drinks. Once their victims were intoxicated and incapable of resisting, they would lure them to an abandoned room.<ref name=\"gang rape\" /><ref>{{cite news|url=http://archive.japantoday.com/jp/shukan/184 |title=Gang rape spotlights dirty deeds at Waseda campus |publisher=[[Japan Today]] |date=2003-07-01 |access-date=2008-04-08 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080615024248/http://archive.japantoday.com/jp/shukan/184 |archive-date=2008-06-15 |df= }}</ref> Wada was arrested on June 9, 2003. His circle's 13 other members were also arrested for gang rape.<ref name=\"gang rape\" /> Super Free was dissolved in June 22, 2003.\n\nWada was indicted for three counts of rape. On November 2, 2004, the [[Tokyo District Court]] sentenced him to 14 years in prison, a comparatively heavy sentence under Japan's postwar sentencing guidelines.<ref>[http://www.search.japantimes.co.jp/cgi-bin/nn20041103a2.html Gang-rape ringleader gets 14 years]{{dead link|date=September 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }} ''[[The Japan Times]]'', November 3, 2004</ref> He appealed the verdict.<ref>[http://search.japantimes.co.jp/cgi-bin/nn20041118b2.html Super Free ringleader appeals 14-year term for gang rapes] ''[[The Japan Times]]'', November 18, 2004</ref> On June 2, 2005, the [[Tokyo High Court]] rejected the appeal and upheld the original sentence.<ref>[http://search.japantimes.co.jp/cgi-bin/nn20050603a5.html High court upholds 14-year sentence for gang-rape leader] ''[[The Japan Times]]'', June 3, 2005</ref> On November 1, 2005, the [[Supreme Court of Japan]] followed suit.<ref>[http://search.japantimes.co.jp/cgi-bin/nn20051103a2.html Appeal by Super Free gang rapist rejected] ''[[The Japan Times]]'', November 3, 2005</ref>\n\nAfter their arrest, a statute for the prosecution of gang rape was established under the [[Criminal Code of Japan]]. In January 2006, three students in [[Kyoto University]] were arrested for gang rape under this penal code.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://search.japantimes.co.jp/cgi-bin/nn20060127a3.html |title=Kyoto University trio held in suspected gang rapes |publisher=[[The Japan Times]] |date=2006-01-27| accessdate=2008-01-17}}</ref>\n\n[[Seiichi Ota]], a Japanese [[cabinet minister]], was heavily criticized after he issued a statement regarding the case, saying \"At least gang rapists are still vigorous. Isn't that at least a little closer to normal?\" on June 26, 2003. He later reported that his statement was taken out of context, and that he didn't have the chance to further comment on the topic.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/asia-pacific/3025240.stm | work=BBC News | title=Fury over Japan rape gaffe | date=2003-06-27 | accessdate=2010-05-24}}</ref>\n\nThen Chief Cabinet Secretary [[Yasuo Fukuda]] was reported to have made highly controversial comments during an off-the-record discussion with reporters in June 2003 regarding the victims of rape by the members of Super Free, according to an article in the weekly magazine Shukan Bunshun. The magazine quoted Fukuda as saying: \"There are women who look like they are saying 'Do it to me'. Those who have that kind of appearance are at fault, because men are black panthers.\" In response, Fukuda claimed that the ''[[Sh\u016bkan Bunshun]]'' had distorted his comments, stating that he had never intended to defend rape, and told a parliamentary panel afterwards that rape was \"a criminal act and an atrocious crime\".<ref>\"[http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/asia-pacific/3042316.stm Japan rape victims 'asking for it'],\" ''BBC News'', 3 July 2003.</ref><ref>\"[http://findarticles.com/p/articles/mi_m0XPQ/is_2003_July_8/ai_104847267 Fukuda denies making remarks defending alleged gang rapists], ''Kyodo'', 8 July 2003</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=BTxZXKsJdGU&feature=fvw Video produced by ''ABC Australia'' about ''Super Free'' on Youtube (7m18)]\n{{Waseda University}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Super Free}}\n[[Category:Crime in Japan]]\n[[Category:2003 in Tokyo]]\n[[Category:Organized crime groups in Japan]]\n[[Category:Organizations established in 1982]]\n[[Category:2003 disestablishments in Japan]]\n[[Category:Rape in Japan]]\n[[Category:Waseda University]]\n[[Category:1982 establishments in Japan]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox organization\n| name                = Super Free\n| native_name         = \u30b9\u30fc\u30d1\u30fc\u30d5\u30ea\u30fc\n| former_name         =\n| image               = \n| image_border        =\n| size                = <!-- default 200px -->\n| alt                 = <!-- alt text; see [[WP:ALT]] -->\n| caption             = \n| map                 =\n| map_size            = <!-- map size, optional, default 250px -->\n| map_alt             = <!-- map alt text -->\n| map_caption         =\n| map2                =\n| abbreviation        =\n| motto               =\n| predecessor         =\n| successor           =\n| formation           = 1982\n| founder             = <!-- or | founders = -->\n| dissolution         = 2003\n| merger              =\n| merged              =\n| type                = [[Yugen kaisha]]\n| status              = <!-- ad hoc, treaty, foundation, etc -->\n| purpose             = <!-- focus as e.g. humanitarian, peacekeeping, etc -->\n| professional_title  = <!-- for professional associations -->\n| headquarters        = \n| location            = \n| coords              = <!-- Coordinates of location using {{Coord}} -->\n| region_served       = [[Japan]]\n| services            =\n| membership          =\n| language            = \n| general             = <!-- Secretary General -->\n| leader_title        =\n| leader_name         =\n| leader_title2       =\n| leader_name2        =\n| leader_title3       =\n| leader_name3        =\n| leader_title4       =\n| leader_name4        =\n| board_of_directors  =\n| key_people          =\n| main_organ          = <!-- gral. assembly, board of directors, etc -->\n| parent_organization = \n| subsidiaries        =\n| affiliations        =\n| budget              =\n| num_staff           =\n| num_volunteers      =\n| slogan              =\n}}\n\n{{nihongo|'''Super Free'''|\u30b9\u30fc\u30d1\u30fc\u30d5\u30ea\u30fc|S\u016bp\u0101-fur\u012b}} or its shortened form {{nihongo|'''S\u016bfuri'''|\u30b9\u30fc\u30d5\u30ea}} was an inter-university rave event club, mainly comprising students of [[Waseda University]] in [[Tokyo]], [[Japan]]. The leader of the club along with various students from Waseda and other universities in Tokyo was arrested and convicted for rape and, subsequently, the club was dubbed by several English media outlets as a \"rape club\".<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.timesonline.co.uk/tol/life_and_style/article1165356.ece|title=Rape clubs: A stain on its elite students that Japan cannot face|first=Leo|last=Lewis|publisher=[[The Times]]|date=2003-10-03|accessdate=2010-09-02}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cbsnews.com/stories/2003/09/02/world/main571280.shtml|title=Rape Debate In Japan|first=Lauren|last=Johnston|publisher=[[CBS]]|date=2003-09-02|accessdate=2010-09-02}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.abc.net.au/news/stories/2004/11/02/1233322.htm|title=Elite club leader gets 14 years jail for gang rapes|publisher=[[ABC Online]]|date=2004-11-02|accessdate=2010-09-02}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.smh.com.au/articles/2003/07/04/1057179159324.html|title=Japan searches soul after divisive rape case|first=Shane|last=Green|publisher=[[The Sydney Morning Herald]]|date=2003-07-05|accessdate=2010-09-02}}</ref> Its leader was {{nihongo|Shin'ichir\u014d Wada|\u548c\u7530 \u771f\u4e00\u90ce|''Wada Shin'ichir\u014d''|born July 30, 1974, in [[Kawasaki, Kanagawa|Kawasaki]], [[Kanagawa Prefecture]]}}. Members of the group were convicted of raping three women, but the real number of victims is unknown.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/worldnews/asia/japan/1475762/Student-rape-mastermind-jailed.html |title=Student rape mastermind jailed |publisher=[[The Daily Telegraph|Telegraph]] |date=2004-11-03| accessdate=2008-07-02 | location=London | first=Colin | last=Joyce}}</ref> Since their arrests, and the club's dissolution, twelve other women have been identified as victims.<ref name=\"gang rape\">{{\ncite news\n | first = Deborah | last = Cameron\n | url=http://www.theage.com.au/articles/2004/11/03/1099362217587.html?from=storylhs\n | title=Gang rape club lured Tokyo girls\n | newspaper = [[The Age|Age]]\n | publisher= [[Fairfax Media|Fairfax]]\n | date=2004-11-04| accessdate=2008-01-17\n| location=Melbourne}}</ref> The club was also incorporated as {{nihongo| Super Free [[Y\u016bgen gaisha]] (Limited)|\u6709\u9650\u4f1a\u793e\u30b9\u30fc\u30d1\u30fc\u30d5\u30ea\u30fc}}.\n\nSuper Free was established as a university social club in 1982.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://search.japantimes.co.jp/cgi-bin/nn20040409a3.html|title=College gang-rape trio get up to 32 months|publisher=The Japan Times|date=2004-04-09|accessdate=2009-07-10}}</ref> Wada was a student at Waseda University before being arrested.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.theage.com.au/cgi-bin/common/popupPrintArticle.pl?path=/articles/2003/07/04/1057179156476.html |title=Revealed: the workings of a uni rape club |publisher=[[The Age]] |date=2003-07-05 |access-date=2008-01-17 |location=Melbourne |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071121093616/http://www.theage.com.au/cgi-bin/common/popupPrintArticle.pl?path=%2Farticles%2F2003%2F07%2F04%2F1057179156476.html |archive-date=2007-11-21 |url-status=dead |df= }}</ref> He entered Waseda University in 1994 and became the organizer of \"Super Free\" in 1995. It had 14 members as of 2003. Super Free was a highly successful inter-university rave event club, to the point that it was incorporated, having 5 branches nationwide, 30-odd employees and an office in Roppongi. According to the indictment, the club organized parties and social gatherings at a public night-club in [[Roppongi]]. The members of Super Free would scout for potential victims among the public, and befriend them offering drinks. Once their victims were intoxicated and incapable of resisting, they would lure them to an abandoned room.<ref name=\"gang rape\" /><ref>{{cite news|url=http://archive.japantoday.com/jp/shukan/184 |title=Gang rape spotlights dirty deeds at Waseda campus |publisher=[[Japan Today]] |date=2003-07-01 |access-date=2008-04-08 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080615024248/http://archive.japantoday.com/jp/shukan/184 |archive-date=2008-06-15 |df= }}</ref> Wada was arrested on June 9, 2003. His circle's 13 other members were also arrested for gang rape.<ref name=\"gang rape\" /> Super Free was dissolved in June 22, 2003.\n\nWada was indicted for three counts of rape. On November 2, 2004, the [[Tokyo District Court]] sentenced him to 14 years in prison, a comparatively heavy sentence under Japan's postwar sentencing guidelines.<ref>[http://www.search.japantimes.co.jp/cgi-bin/nn20041103a2.html Gang-rape ringleader gets 14 years]{{dead link|date=September 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }} ''[[The Japan Times]]'', November 3, 2004</ref> He appealed the verdict.<ref>[http://search.japantimes.co.jp/cgi-bin/nn20041118b2.html Super Free ringleader appeals 14-year term for gang rapes] ''[[The Japan Times]]'', November 18, 2004</ref> On June 2, 2005, the [[Tokyo High Court]] rejected the appeal and upheld the original sentence.<ref>[http://search.japantimes.co.jp/cgi-bin/nn20050603a5.html High court upholds 14-year sentence for gang-rape leader] ''[[The Japan Times]]'', June 3, 2005</ref> On November 1, 2005, the [[Supreme Court of Japan]] followed suit.<ref>[http://search.japantimes.co.jp/cgi-bin/nn20051103a2.html Appeal by Super Free gang rapist rejected] ''[[The Japan Times]]'', November 3, 2005</ref>\n\nAfter their arrest, a statute for the prosecution of gang rape was established under the [[Criminal Code of Japan]]. In January 2006, three students in [[Kyoto University]] were arrested for gang rape under this penal code.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://search.japantimes.co.jp/cgi-bin/nn20060127a3.html |title=Kyoto University trio held in suspected gang rapes |publisher=[[The Japan Times]] |date=2006-01-27| accessdate=2008-01-17}}</ref>\n\n[[Seiichi Ota]], a Japanese [[cabinet minister]], was heavily criticized after he issued a statement regarding the case, saying \"At least gang rapists are still vigorous. Isn't that at least a little closer to normal?\" on June 26, 2003. He later reported that his statement was taken out of context, and that he didn't have the chance to further comment on the topic.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/asia-pacific/3025240.stm | work=BBC News | title=Fury over Japan rape gaffe | date=2003-06-27 | accessdate=2010-05-24}}</ref>\n\nThen Chief Cabinet Secretary [[Yasuo Fukuda]] was reported to have made highly controversial comments during an off-the-record discussion with reporters in June 2003 regarding the victims of rape by the members of Super Free, according to an article in the weekly magazine Shukan Bunshun. The magazine quoted Fukuda as saying: \"There are women who look like they are saying 'Do it to me'. Those who have that kind of appearance are at fault, because men are black panthers.\" In response, Fukuda claimed that the ''[[Sh\u016bkan Bunshun]]'' had distorted his comments, stating that he had never intended to defend rape, and told a parliamentary panel afterwards that rape was \"a criminal act and an atrocious crime\".<ref>\"[http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/asia-pacific/3042316.stm Japan rape victims 'asking for it'],\" ''BBC News'', 3 July 2003.</ref><ref>\"[http://findarticles.com/p/articles/mi_m0XPQ/is_2003_July_8/ai_104847267 Fukuda denies making remarks defending alleged gang rapists], ''Kyodo'', 8 July 2003</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=BTxZXKsJdGU&feature=fvw Video produced by ''ABC Australia'' about ''Super Free'' on Youtube (7m18)]\n{{Waseda University}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Super Free}}\n[[Category:Crime in Japan]]\n[[Category:2003 in Japan]]\n[[Category:Organized crime groups in Japan]]\n[[Category:Organizations established in 1982]]\n[[Category:2003 disestablishments in Japan]]\n[[Category:Rape in Japan]]\n[[Category:Waseda University]]\n[[Category:1982 establishments in Japan]]\n", "name_user": "KingSkyLord", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eExternal links", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Super_Free"}
{"title_page": "Athletics at the 1988 Summer Olympics \u2013 Women's 800 metres", "text_new": "{{Infobox Olympic event\n|event = Women's 800 metres\n|games = 1988 Summer\n|image =\n|caption =\n|venue = [[Olympic Stadium (Seoul)|Olympic Stadium]]\n|dates = {{Date|1988-9-24}} (heats)<br />{{Date|1988-9-25}} (semi-finals)<br />{{Date|1988-9-26}} (final)\n|competitors = 29\n|nations = 19\n|win_value = 1:56.10\n|longnames = yes\n|gold = [[Sigrun Wodars]]\n|goldNOC = GDR\n|silver = [[Christine Wachtel]]\n|silverNOC = GDR\n|bronze = [[Kim Gallagher]]\n|bronzeNOC = USA\n|prev = [[Athletics at the 1984 Summer Olympics \u2013 Women's 800 metres|1984]]\n|next = [[Athletics at the 1992 Summer Olympics \u2013 Women's 800 metres|1992]]\n}}\n{{AthleticsAt1988SummerOlympics}}\n\nThe '''[[800 metres|Women's 800 metres]]''' at the '''[[Athletics at the 1988 Summer Olympics|1988 Summer Olympics]]''' in [[Seoul, South Korea]] had an entry list of 29 competitors, with four qualifying heats (29) and two semi-finals (16), before the final (8) took off on Monday September 26, 1988.<ref name=\"SR\">{{cite web |url=https://www.sports-reference.com/olympics/summer/1988/ATH/womens-800-metres.html |title=Athletics at the 1988 Seoul Games: Women's 800 metres |accessdate=21 October 2017 |work=sports-reference.com}}</ref>\n\n==Medalists==\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\" text-align:center; font-size:110%;\" width=\"35%\"\n|-\n|{{OlympicGoldMedalist|[[Sigrun Wodars]]|GDR|1988 Summer}}\n|-\n|{{OlympicSilverMedalist|[[Christine Wachtel]]|GDR|1988 Summer}}\n|-\n|{{OlympicBronzeMedalist|[[Kim Gallagher]]|USA|1988 Summer}}\n|}\n\n==Records==\nThese were the standing world and Olympic records (in minutes) prior to the 1988 Summer Olympics.\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"font-size:95%;\"\n|- \n! World Record\n| 1:53.28\n| {{flagicon|TCH}} [[Jarmila Kratochv\u00edlov\u00e1]]\n| [[Munich]] ([[West Germany|FGR]])\n| July 26, 1983\n|-\n! Olympic Record\n| 1:53.43\n| {{flagicon|URS}} [[Nadiya Olizarenko]]\n| [[Moscow]] ([[USSR|URS]])\n| July 27, 1980\n|}\n\n==Summary==\nThe final started with returning silver medalist [[Kim Gallagher]] running the fastest first turn to take the lead at the break.  But that was short lived as the two East German teammates ran past her down the backstretch, [[Christine Wachtel]] on the inside, leading [[Sigrun Wodars]] tight on her shoulder.  [[Inna Yevseyeva]] moved to the outside to run past Gallagher, with [[Slobodanka \u010colovi\u0107]] in her wake while Gallagher had her teammate [[Delisa Walton-Floyd]] a step behind her.  As Yevseyeva moved forward, the first lap was a fast 56.43.  Through the penultimate turn, Wodars took the lead and pushed the pace.  Behind her, a break began to form as Walton-Floyd, [[Maite Z\u00fa\u00f1iga]] and [[Diane Edwards]] couldn't keep up.  Wachtel made up a little lost ground on the backstretch and pulled shoulder to shoulder with Wodars by the 600 mark in 1:25.5, then taking the lead into the final turn.  It was a lead in formality only as Wodars, Yevseyeva and \u010colovi\u0107 lining up in close order drill, getting ready to pounce coming off the turn.  As the straightaway neared, Gallagher seized the gap on the inside, running through to Wachtel's heels.  Yevseyeva struggled to keep up, as Gallagher moved to the outside of Wodars, leaving \u010colovi\u0107 with nowhere to run and the first three all having clear running room to the finish line.  Just like the [[1987 World Championships in Athletics \u2013 Women's 800 metres|World Championships]] the year before, Wachtel had a slight edge coming off the turn and a long history of winning, but in the big ones, Wodars had slightly more speed to edge ahead and take the gold even more decisively.  The race lost, Wachtel struggled toward the end but Gallagher couldn't catch her for the silver.\n\n==Final==\n{| border=\"1\" cellspacing=\"2\" cellpadding=\"5\" style=\"border-collapse: collapse; font-size: 90%;\"\n|- bgcolor=\"cccccc\"\n!RANK\n!style=\"w